04421nam a22007215i 9781512807059DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161968pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)980261026  a97815128070597 a10.9783/97815128070592doi  a(DE-B1597)475544  a(OCoLC)979743797  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aRC576.S49 7aMED1050002bisacsh04a362.21 aSilverstein, Max, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPsychiatric Aftercare :bPlanning for a Community Mental Health Service /cMax Silverstein.  aReprint 2016 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©1968  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnniversary Collection00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tPart I.The Nature of Psychiatric Aftercare -- tPart II. The Planning Process -- tAppendices -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEach year about 325,000 persons are admitted as patients to public mental hospitals in the United States. Less than half are first admissions; 175,000 are readmissions. And each year about 310,000 patients leave the public mental hospitals. They undertake the hazards of living again, as ex-patients, in the community. More than half will return, at some time, to hospital. The highest proportion will return within the first year after release.Mental health workers, planners, and administrators hold that many more ex-patients would sustain community tenure if appropriate follow-up aftercare services were available to them. But no one is sure to what extent this is so. This studies aspects of the aftercare problems of over 10,000 patients released from public mental hospitals. It highlights major aftercare service needs of released patients, the availability of aftercare services, the utilization of these services by ex-patients, and the relationship between utilization of services and community tenure.The study provides answers to the following questions:1. What are the specific aftercare needs of released patients?2. To what extent are aftercare services available?3. To what degree do ex-patients utilize aftercare services?4. Does utilization affect community tenure?This book is divided into two parts. Part I reports major statewide findings and interpretations. Part II focuses on background, methodology, and data specifically applicable to planning regions and service areas within the state. Readers interested primarily in the broad overview of aftercare will find Part I useful in itself. For those interested, in addition, in the planning process technique of assessment, comparative data and analysis, Part II will be a helpful supplement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMentally illxRehabilitation. 7aMEDICAL / Psychiatry / General.2bisacsh  aCaregiving.  aHealth.  aMedicine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280705940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512807059423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781512807059.jpg  a978-3-11-044252-6  University of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK